Contagious agalactia - United Kingdom
-------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 31 Oct 2014 from Dr Nigel Gibbens, Chief Veterinary Officer, Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, London, United Kingdom

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 24 Oct 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 24 Oct 2014
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: sub-clinical disease
Causal agent: _Mycoplasma agalactiae_
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to the whole country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Abergavenny, Monmouthshire, Wales
Date of start of the outbreak: 24 Oct 2014
Outbreak status: resolved (25 Oct 2014)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Goats / 4 / 1 / 0 / 4 / 0 /
Affected population: One out of 4 goats in a single consignment imported onto a smallholding from an area endemic for contagious agalactia tested positive for the pathogen _Mycoplasma agalactiae_.

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Goats / 25 / 0 / 0 / 100
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: introduction of new live animals.
Epidemiological comments:
- The animals were tested as part of our risk based post import checks regime and serology results were inconclusive for one animal.
- Restrictions were placed on all the animals and further tests detected the presence of the pathogen in milk samples from that animal.
- All animals were clinically well but have been humanely destroyed and cleansing and disinfection were carried out on the small holding.
- No other susceptible animals were present at the holding and there are no contact tracings with other susceptible species. The initial epidemiological investigations have concluded that the risk of spread of the pathogen is very low and the United Kingdom (UK) Veterinary Services have not confirmed the presence of the disease in the UK. Note by the OIE World Animal Health Information and Analysis Department: Since this is the 1st time that contagious agalactia is identified in the history of the country, the reason for notification as 1st occurrence applies to the country but the event is in fact limited to a zone.

Control measures
Measures applied: stamping out; quarantine; movement control inside the country; disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); vaccination prohibited; no treatment of affected animals.
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) Weybridge (OIE's reference laboratory) / Goats / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 24 Oct 2014 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

