Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Contagious agalactia is a disease of sheep and goats that is characterised by mastitis, arthritis, and keratoconjunctivitis, and has been known for nearly 200 years. It occurs in Europe, Asia, the USA, and North Africa, and is mainly caused by _Mycoplasma agalactiae_ (Ma). An upsurge of contagious agalactia, caused by Ma, has been seen in sheep in Spain and France recently with increased cases reported in and around the Pyrenees and new outbreaks being reported in Corsica. Frequent and numerous outbreaks occur in Iran and Mongolia. In recent years, _M. capricolum_ subsp. _Capricolum_ (Mcc) and _M. mycoides_ subsp. _Capri_ (formerly _M. mycoides_ subsp. _mycoides_ LC [LC = large colonies]) have also been isolated from sheep and goats with mastitis and arthritis in many countries, including those in South America and Australasia.

For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods, please refer to OIE Terrestrial Manual 2014, Chapter 2.7.5 "Contagious agalactia", available at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.07.05_CONT_AGALACT.pdf (adopted by the World Assembly of Delegates of the OIE in May 2013)

The following information was obtained from: "Mycoplasma diseases of ruminants 2008" (http://tinyurl.com/nw62to6, CAB International (Nicholas R, Ayling R, McAuliffe L, editors), chapter 8 "Contagious agalactia" pp. 98-113:

- Geographical distribution
"CA [contagious agalactia] has been reported in southern Europe, in particular France, Portugal, Spain, Greece, and Italy (Bergonier et al, 1997), the Balkans including FYR Macedonia, Bulgaria, Albania (Cokrevski et al, 2001), Turkey (Ozdemir et al, 2005), Israel (Bar-Moshe et al, 1984), Jordan (Al-Momani et al, 2006), India, the USA, South America, and North Africa (Nicholas, 2002). Serious problems exist in Iran, where over 1300 cases were reported in 2006 (OIE, 2008). _M. mycoides_ LC has also been reported from arthritic goats and cattle recently in New Zealand (OIE, 2004)."

- Molecular epidemiology
In this section the following is noted: "As _M. agalactiae_ shows differing prevalence across the world, and as it is currently absent from some countries, notably the UK, there is a need for molecular epidemiological techniques which enable a high degree of strain differentiation, allowing the tracing of the source of disease outbreaks."

For further information on contagious agalactia, including a chapter on geographic distribution, subscribers are referred to the article published in 2014, "_Mycoplasma agalactiae_, an Etiological Agent of Contagious Agalactia in Small Ruminants: A Review," available at http://www.hindawi.com/journals/vmi/2014/286752/

OIE's internationally agreed requirements pertaining to contagious agalactia are spelled out in 14.4 chapter of OIE's Terrestrial Animal Health Code, available at http://tinyurl.com/kfcbnoh.

Pictures of clinical signs and post mortem lesions, can be seen at http://tinyurl.com/nw62to6

There is no evidence that _M. agalactiae_ is a threat to human health (http://www.cfsph.iastate.edu/Factsheets/pdfs/contagious_agalactia.pdf). - Mods.CRD/AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2926784,5697.]
